  "DNA and RNA": "",
  "The two types of nucleic acids are deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) and ribonucleic acid (RNA). DNA stores genetic information, while RNA plays various roles in gene expression.": "",
  "What are the three components of a nucleotide?": "",
  "Nitrogenous base, pentose sugar, and phosphate group": "",
  "Fatty acid, glycerol, and phosphate group": "",
  "Amino acid, phosphate group, and sugar": "",
  "Nitrogenous base, hexose sugar, and hydroxyl group": "",
  "Each nucleotide consists of a nitrogenous base (A, T/U, G, or C), a five-carbon (pentose) sugar (deoxyribose in DNA, ribose in RNA), and a phosphate group.": "",
  "Which nitrogenous base is found in RNA but not in DNA?": "",
  "Cytosine": "",
  "Thymine": "",
  "Guanine": "",
  "Uracil": "",
  "Uracil (U) replaces thymine (T) in RNA. Both uracil and thymine are pyrimidines that pair with adenine, but thymine has a methyl group that uracil lacks.": "",
  "In DNA, adenine always pairs with which other base?": "",
  "According to Chargaff's rules, adenine (A) pairs with thymine (T) through two hydrogen bonds in DNA. Guanine (G) pairs with cytosine (C) through three hydrogen bonds.": "",
  "What type of bond connects nucleotides in a single strand of DNA?": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds": "",
  "Glycosidic bonds": "",
  "Phosphodiester bonds": "",
  "Peptide bonds": "",
  "Phosphodiester bonds connect the 3' hydroxyl group of one nucleotide's sugar to the 5' phosphate group of the next nucleotide, forming the sugar-phosphate backbone of the nucleic acid strand.": "",
  "How many hydrogen bonds form between guanine and cytosine in DNA?": "",
  "1": "",
  "2": "",
  "4": "",
  "3": "",
  "Guanine and cytosine form three hydrogen bonds, making G-C base pairs stronger than A-T base pairs (which form only two hydrogen bonds). DNA with more G-C content has a higher melting temperature.": "",
  "What sugar is found in the backbone of DNA?": "",
  "Glucose": "",
  "Deoxyribose": "",
  "Fructose": "",
  "Ribose": "",
  "DNA contains deoxyribose, which lacks an oxygen atom at the 2' carbon compared to ribose (found in RNA). This structural difference makes DNA more chemically stable than RNA.": "",
  "DNA strands run in opposite directions and are said to be:": "",
  "Perpendicular": "",
  "Complementary only": "",
  "Parallel": "",
  "Antiparallel": "",
  "The two strands of DNA run in opposite directions: one strand runs 5' to 3' while the complementary strand runs 3' to 5'. This antiparallel arrangement is essential for DNA replication and base pairing.": "",
  "Which type of RNA carries amino acids to the ribosome during translation?": "",
  "rRNA": "",
  "mRNA": "",
  "snRNA": "",
  "tRNA": "",
  "Transfer RNA (tRNA) carries specific amino acids to the ribosome and has an anticodon that base-pairs with the mRNA codon, ensuring the correct amino acid is added to the growing polypeptide chain.": "",
  "If a DNA strand reads 5'-ATCGGA-3', what is the sequence of the complementary strand?": "",
  "5'-ATCGGA-3'": "",
  "3'-TAGCCT-5'": "",
  "3'-AUCGGA-5'": "",
  "5'-TAGCCT-3'": "",
  "The complementary strand runs antiparallel and follows base pairing rules (A-T, C-G). For 5'-ATCGGA-3', the complementary strand is 3'-TAGCCT-5'.": "",
  "What is a nucleotide?": "",
  "A carbohydrate used for energy in the nucleus": "",
  "A lipid molecule found in the nuclear membrane": "",
  "The monomer of nucleic acids, consisting of a nitrogenous base, a pentose sugar, and a phosphate group": "",
  "A polymer of amino acids that stores genetic information": "",
  "A nucleotide is the basic building block (monomer) of nucleic acids. It has three parts: a nitrogenous base, a five-carbon sugar (ribose or deoxyribose), and one or more phosphate groups.": "",
  "What does 'complementary base pairing' mean?": "",
  "Bases on the same strand of DNA pair with each other": "",
  "The specific pairing of nitrogenous bases through hydrogen bonds: adenine with thymine (or uracil in RNA) and guanine with cytosine": "",
  "Bases pair based on their size only, not their chemical structure": "",
  "Any base can pair with any other base in DNA": "",
  "Complementary base pairing is the specific hydrogen bonding between purine and pyrimidine bases: A pairs with T (two H-bonds) in DNA or A with U in RNA, and G pairs with C (three H-bonds) in both.": "",
  "What is a phosphodiester bond?": "",
  "A hydrogen bond between complementary bases on opposite strands": "",
  "A covalent bond linking the 3' carbon of one nucleotide's sugar to the 5' phosphate of the next nucleotide, forming the sugar-phosphate backbone": "",
  "A bond between a nitrogenous base and a sugar molecule": "",
  "A bond between two phosphate groups in ATP": "",
  "A phosphodiester bond is the covalent linkage in the nucleic acid backbone, connecting the 3'-OH of one nucleotide's sugar to the 5'-phosphate of the adjacent nucleotide through a phosphate group.": "",
  "What does the term 'antiparallel' mean in the context of DNA structure?": "",
  "The two DNA strands are identical in sequence": "",
  "The two strands of the DNA double helix run in opposite directions, with one strand oriented 5' to 3' and the other 3' to 5'": "",
  "The bases on each strand face in opposite directions": "",
  "DNA strands are perpendicular to each other": "",
  "Antiparallel means the two strands of the DNA double helix run in opposite 5'-to-3' directions. This arrangement is critical for complementary base pairing and has important implications for DNA replication.": "",
