  "Both viruses convert their RNA to DNA before translation, since the prevailing theory about directly would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "The first virus has DNA, not RNA; only the second has RNA, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual directly mechanisms at work": "",
  "Positive-sense RNA viruses have genomes that function directly as mRNA for translation. Retroviruses use reverse transcriptase to convert their RNA genome into DNA, which integrates into the host chromosome as a provirus before being transcribed.": "",
  "A genetic counselor explains to a couple that their child's rare disease is caused by a trinucleotide repeat expansion in a gene (e.g., Huntington's disease, where CAG repeats expand). The counselor notes that the number of repeats tends to increase in successive generations, causing earlier and more severe onset. What molecular phenomenon does this describe?": "",
